South African Stocks Fall, Snapping Two Days of Gains, Led by Wilson-Bayly

-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 
2011-02-15T16:54:04Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-15/south-african-stocks-sacoil-holdings-wilson-bayly-holmes-shares-move.html
  South Africa ’s FTSE/JSE  Africa  All
Share Index snapped two days of gains, declining 33.78, or 0.1
percent, to 33,060.28 at the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.    Litha Healthcare Group Ltd . (LHG SJ), a healthcare company,
advanced the most since Dec. 9, jumping 20 cents, or 8.5
percent, to 2.55 rand. The group said headline earnings, or
profit per share before one-time items, goodwill and
amortization, probably increased by up to 150 percent in the 12
months ended December. Life Healthcare also extended its
contract to supply pediatric vaccines to the South African
government until the end of 2016.  SacOil Holdings Ltd. (SCL SJ), an oil and natural gas
explorer, advanced 7 cents, or 4.1 percent, to 1.76 rand, the
highest since Dec. 13. The company is in talks with a number of
potential investors about its oil block in the Democratic
Republic of Congo, Chief Executive Officer Robin Vela said.    Tiger Brands Ltd . (TBS SJ), South Africa’s largest food
company, dropped 2.59 rand, or 1.4 percent, to 180.28 rand, the
lowest since Sept. 1. The food company said in a statement it
has agreed to buy powdered seasoning and beverages group Davita
Trading Ltd. for about 1.35 billion rand ($184 million) in cash
to expand its presence in Africa.  WG Wearne Ltd. (WEA SJ), a concrete maker, dropped to the
lowest level since Jan. 5, falling 4 cents, or 18 percent, to 18
cents. The company said it has applied to the High Court to seek
a moratorium on its debt repayments for a 24 months to January
2013.    Wilson Bayly Holmes-Ovcon Ltd . (WBO SJ), a construction
company, declined 1.45 rand, or 1.2 percent, to 122.80 rand. The
company said the six months ended 31 December 2010 will show a
15 percent to 20 percent drop in headline earnings, or profit
before one-time items, goodwill and amortization, and a 10
percent to 15 percent decline in earnings per share.  To contact the reporter on this story:
